Here are both approaches.

## 1. Route registration (AppShell.xaml.cs)

```csharp
public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
    }
}
```

## 2. Navigate from ProductListPage

```csharp
// Approach A — string ID via query string
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");
}

// Approach B — full object via ShellNavigationQueryParameters
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var parameters = new ShellNavigationQueryParameters
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
}
```

## 3. Receive on the ViewModel with IQueryAttributable

```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _productId;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private Product _product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A — string parameter arrives as object, convert it
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // Load full product from a service using ProductId...
        }

        // Approach B — full object passed directly
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
        }
    }
}
```

## 4. Wire the ViewModel to the page

```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsPage : ContentPage
{
    public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- **Query string** (`?productId=42`) — values arrive as strings; best for simple IDs and deep-link support.
- **ShellNavigationQueryParameters** — passes the live object reference; avoids serialization but doesn't support deep links.
- Both approaches deliver data to the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` method, so you can handle either (or both) in one place.
- Always `await` `GoToAsync` to avoid race conditions.
